DBT Code Pages for Textfiles

Introduction

A code page is a widely-recognized system of matching numbers with unique characters that they represent. A textfile is a long list of numbers. We now have a code page that includes virtually all characters (called Unicode). But in previous years, the list of characters in a code page was limited to 256 characters. The solution was Code Pages, each with a different group of characters.

The history and proliferation of code pages is a mirror of the development of computers. The first code page was invented by IBM (called EBCDIC), which is now shunned by all. ASCII was a standard, but only for the first 128 characters. Many code pages use the same 128 characters at the beginning (called the low bit characters), but then vary extensively on the next 128 characters (called the high bit characters).

After ASCII, IBM created a set of code pages. Originally Microsoft co-operated with IBM, and used common code pages with IBM. In the 1990's, these two companies stopped co-operating, and Microsoft made its own version of key code pages. Before Unicode, various Asian nations set up their own systems for handling their scripts on computers, Many of these systems are still popular today. At one point there was an Icelandic code page. Then a new Icelandic code page was set up just to add the Euro symbol.

This explains why there are a lot of code pages. But it does not explain how to cope with this long list of different code pages presented by DBT. Here are some basic observations:

  • When in doubt, use WINDOWS-1252 as your code page. This is the most common code page.
  • Some users will come to this knowing exactly what they want. They have a Polish file using WINDOWS-1250 or a Japanese textfile using Shift JIS; they know what it is, and they can select the right choice.
  • If you import with WINDOWS-1252 code page, and everything is correct except for curling quotes, then you have a code page problem.
  • Specifically, if you import with WINDOWS-1252 code page and curling quotes are accented upper case O's, then you really have a Macintosh textfile (i.e. use a Mac code page instead).
  • Several of the Macintosh code pages for Asian languages are the same as a popular existing texfile format. This may prove useful.
  • Some software, such as Microsoft Word has a feature called Code Page sniffing. Word can detect and guess the most appropriate code page. DBT cannot do this. You might use Word to detect the type of file, and then use DBT for similar files now that you know the code page.
  • The list of DBT supported code pages includes all of the variations of Unicode (including UTF-8).
